INSERT INTO public.pe_narratives (pe_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, accomplishments, planned_program, performance_metrics, other_program_funding, raw_text, content_hash, section_hashes, source_pdf, source_page, ingested_at) VALUES ($$0604286N$$, 2026, $$Project 0311 - NAVAIR Advanced/Additive Manufacturing provides for the development of the Advanced/Additive Manufacturing/3D printing process, material verification
and qualification to support deployment of Advanced/Additive Manufacturing (AM) capability to Fleet Depot and Level II Maintenance level facilities, as well as provides
for the qualification, validation, testing and incorporation of private industry Additive Manufacturing initiatives across the Naval Aviation enterprise to include NAVSUP
and DLA. Additionally, Advanced/Additive Manufacturing funds Cooperative Research and Development Activities (CRADAs) support with industry partners and
next generation AM. This effort will fund the development, test, and approval of additional polymer material data curves, polymer material certification for aviation
applications, and system documentation/training updates of additional high strength polymers for use on deployed AM systems. This will support deployed systems in
producing critical parts for aircraft, support equipment and aircraft launch and recovery equipment, while enhancing Naval Aviation readiness and lethality allowing point
of need part manufacturing to mitigate supply chain gaps, dramatically decreasing Mean Logistics Delay Times (MLDT) and increasing aircraft availability.

Project 0312 - The NAVSEA Additive Manufacturing (AM) program focuses on development and use of AM equipment for Naval applications in land-based and afloat
environments, including system performance requirements, shipboard integration requirements and considerations, material selection, design optimization, equipment
and component certification, and digital engineering integration. Efforts also include consideration of AM across a wide variety of potential applications ensuring
additively manufactured components can meet mission requirements and that system/component technical requirements are updated to leverage AM.

Project 0313 - NAVWAR Digital Integration Advanced Manufacturing
The NAVWAR Digital Advanced Manufacturing Ecosystem (DAME) project provides Navy Advanced Manufacturing (AdvM) technology aligning to Chief of Naval
operations (CNO) priorities to deliver revolutionary capabilities to improve fleet readiness.
Strategic Design 2.0, this program provides the Navy with new capabilities to enable resilient and agile logistics thru advanced manufacturing (AdvM). Investing in AdvM
enhances the fleet's ability to conduct operational logistics in a contested environment and ensures logistics supportability across the austere distributed battlespace.
AdvM technology results in increased operational availability, on demand production of critical systems, and supply chain cost savings.

This effort will identify critical parts suitable for AdvM production in the field; identify AdvM systems appropriate to produce and certify critical parts in the field; analyze
and identify AdvM system implications across doctrine, organization, training, materiel, leadership and education, personnel, facilities and policy (DOTMLPF-P); conduct
end-user training, field experimentation, and fleet exercise technology insertion to validate AdvM system capability and systems integration issues.$$, $$Advanced Manufacturing (AdvM) : In accordance with the National Defense Strategy (NDS), A Design for Maintaining Maritime Superiority 2.0, and Navy Facility
Command (NAVFAC) Strategic Design 2.0, this program provides the Navy with new capabilities to enable resilient and agile logistics thru advanced manufacturing
(AdvM). Investing in AdvM enhances the fleet's ability to conduct operational logistics in a contested environment and ensures logistics supportability across the austere
distributed battlespace. AdvM technology results in increased operational availability, on demand production of critical systems, and supply chain cost savings.

This effort will identify critical parts suitable for AdvM production in the field; identify AdvM systems appropriate to produce and certify critical parts in the field; analyze
and identify AdvM system implications across doctrine, organization, training, materiel, leadership and education, personnel, facilities and policy (DOTMLPF-P); conduct
end-user training, field experimentation, and fleet exercise technology insertion to validate AdvM system capability and systems integration issues.

