interface. The defined interfaces will continue to support current and future payloads. Potential future payloads, advanced energy solutions and enhanced autonomy
and command and control will be developed and evaluated under the Core Technologies PE 0604029N, and/or by other Science and technology organizations, and
integrated into Orca XLUUV when ready. In Q2FY24 The Navy signed a new Top-Level Requirement for a Hunter payload on the JEON XLUUV. This program initiated
under a DARPA/Core Tech effort and is planned to transition to a design, test and fabrication effort in FY26. The Navy is concurrently updating facilities at the Naval
Base Ventura County site for XLUUV testing, training, and workups, in coordination with large, unmanned surface vessel testing for cost efficiencies. In parallel, the
Navy is working through the process to establish future far-forward basing locations. Following successful Government testing, training, and workups at the Naval
Base Ventura County site, the Navy will establish in-theater forward operational capability. In addition, the CAMP is a prototype project using USC 4022 authorities to
assess commercial XLUUV capabilities. The Navy conduct prototyping for extended range, large payload commercially available UUV platforms through a Defense
Innovation Unit (DIU) Commercial Solutions Opening (CSO) using a three (3) phase strategy of written proposal evaluations, in-water demonstration assessments and
cost, schedule, performance negotiations.




