FY 2025 Plans: Title: Missile Systems ($68.029 million):

- Began first phase of competitive design and prototyping contracts for the AUR and MCL to reduce risk prior to
entering Technology Maturation and Risk Reduction. Initiated Underwater Launch planning support.
- Began generating Missile Work Breakdown Structure, Activation Sequence Diagrams, and Building Activation
Sequence Network
- Initiated draft Facility Correlation Drawings, Shore Interface Requirements Documentation, draft Subsystem
Interface Drawings, and draft Operational Sequence Data documents.
- Completed Facilities Program Documentation including development of the Facilities Program Plan, Shore
CONOPS, Facility Requirements Plan, and a draft Facility Activation Plan Developed the Government Reference
Architecture for the AUR.

                                                                               evelopment Program

B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                FY 2024   FY 2025
- Began interface development work to define Missile to Warhead Integration Unit interfaces and Missile to
Shipboard interfaces.
- Began Missile system development test and qualification plans.
- Began preliminary CONOP/CONEMP development for the purposes of system design and architecture.

Title: Shipboard Systems ($21.666 million)

- Initiated fire control subsystem and submarine platform systems architecture trade studies, enabling down-
selection of the weapon system platform physical architecture.
- Initiated fire control subsystem requirements development, fire control subsystem functional descriptions and
compliance artifacts; began nuclear fire control, submarine platform systems and mission planning requirements.

Title: Test & Evaluation ($2.200 million)

- Began range capabilities assessment study.
- Continued the development of program required T&E documentation, including TEMP, Test strategy, schedule
and program implementation.
- Began coordination with OPTEVFOR for development of Integrated Evaluation Framework.
- Began planning for upgrades to range infrastructure to support future missile and capabilities testing.

Title: Warhead (WH) and Warhead Interface Unit (WIU) ($14.574 million)

Conducting Phase 6.2 and 6.2A activities for the SLCM-N WH to include, but not limited to:
- Develop lower-level technical, programmatic, procedural guidance, and logistic workflows based on applicable
guidance.
- Develop joint DoD/DOE programmatic documents including Major Impact Report, Joint Integrated Project Plan
Weapon Design and Cost Report Cost Analysis Requirements Document.
- Design and Cost Report Cost Analysis Requirements Document.
- Identify/validate WH subsystem requirements.
- Identify conceptual designs, evaluate design options, and begin long lead development activities.
- Identify rationale for component reuse, remanufacture, or replacement.
- Establish readiness levels for technologies and manufacturing.
- Support development of weapon system nuclear surety architecture to support the Initial Safety Study during
Phase 6.3

